One thing that is important to remember is that actually creating a film

00:05:13.638 --> 00:05:19.288
was very expensive, and cartoons, animated films, were even more so.

00:05:20.598 --> 00:05:23.178
Every scene needed to be drawn by hand.

00:05:23.198 --> 00:05:28.128
You needed lots of people to do it, and this made them very expensive to make.

00:05:29.248 --> 00:05:35.438
Nevertheless, by 1927 Walt Disney had decided that he wanted to go full time

00:05:35.618 --> 00:05:40.868
into cartoon making, and he created a character called Oswald the Lucky Rabbit.

00:05:42.218 --> 00:05:47.184
In the first year, he produced 26 short films with Oswald the Lucky Rabbit.

00:05:48.134 --> 00:05:51.314
His studio would make the cartoons, then they would

00:05:51.324 --> 00:05:54.764
be distributed by a company called Universal Pictures.

00:05:55.914 --> 00:06:00.454
When Walt Disney went back to Universal Pictures for more money to continue

00:06:00.454 --> 00:06:04.438
making the cartoon, he realised that something terrible had happened.

00:06:05.471 --> 00:06:11.558
Universal Pictures, the distribution company, in order to try to save money, had gone

00:06:11.568 --> 00:06:18.530
directly to Walt Disney’s illustrators, his employees, trying to cut Disney’s studio out.

00:06:19.751 --> 00:06:22.920
Surely they can’t do that, the young Disney must have thought.

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:27.243
Oswald The Lucky Rabbit is my creation, someone else

00:06:27.243 --> 00:06:30.723
can’t just make Oswald films without my permission?

00:06:31.883 --> 00:06:36.463
However, looking closely at the contract Disney realised that he

00:06:36.463 --> 00:06:40.983
didn’t actually own the rights to Oswald - Universal Pictures did.

00:06:41.753 --> 00:06:44.143
There was nothing that Walt Disney could do.

00:06:45.393 --> 00:06:50.153
This was a tough lesson for young Walt, but it was to be a valuable one.

00:06:51.073 --> 00:06:54.763
From then on, Disney made sure that he owned everything

00:06:54.773 --> 00:06:58.593
he made, so that this experience could never be repeated.

00:06:59.823 --> 00:07:04.213
As he couldn’t use Oswald, Disney had to come up with a new character,

00:07:04.613 --> 00:07:09.033
a character that you will no doubt now be familiar with - Mickey Mouse.

00:07:10.213 --> 00:07:15.103
Mickey Mouse’s first breakout appearance was in the 1928 film

00:07:15.323 --> 00:07:19.763
‘Steamboat Willie’, which was one of the first ‘sound cartoons’.

00:07:20.503 --> 00:07:25.273
Now, to briefly explain what ‘sound cartoon’ means, and why

00:07:25.273 --> 00:07:29.813
it is important, before ‘sound cartoons’ movies were silent.

00:07:30.187 --> 00:07:35.577
There was normally music, but it wasn’t synchronised to what was happening on the screen.

00:07:36.527 --> 00:07:41.527
With a sound cartoon, what you heard reflected what was happening on screen.

00:07:42.037 --> 00:07:46.777
If on screen a character hit his head, you would hear the bang, and so on.

00:07:47.637 --> 00:07:54.597
To you or me now, this might sound pretty basic, but it was a big development back in 1928.

00:07:55.777 --> 00:07:59.687
After this appearance in Steamboat Willie, Mickey Mouse was an

00:07:59.717 --> 00:08:04.783
almost instant success,  and to this day he is the symbol of Disney.

00:08:06.103 --> 00:08:11.383
Relatively soon after the creation of Mickey Mouse, Disney realised the potential

00:08:11.423 --> 00:08:17.213
of merchandising his characters, he realised that people didn’t just want to watch

00:08:17.293 --> 00:08:22.793
Mickey Mouse on screen, they wanted Mickey Mouse on pencils, on toothbrushes, there

00:08:22.793 --> 00:08:28.053
were Mickey Mouse comic books, and the face of this little mouse was everywhere.

00:08:29.024 --> 00:08:34.114
Not only was this good because Disney was paid by companies to use Mickey Mouse,

00:08:34.394 --> 00:08:40.144
but all of these Mickey Mouse objects acted as adverts for Mickey Mouse movies.

00:08:41.344 --> 00:08:45.724
This is one of the magical parts of the Disney business, which we’ll come on to

00:08:45.724 --> 00:08:50.224
discuss more in the second part of this mini series, but the point here is that

00:08:50.254 --> 00:08:54.514
it was the start of Disney realising that there was a lot of money to be made

00:08:54.574 --> 00:08:59.894
from the characters, which he could then reinvest in making more and more movies.

00:09:01.054 --> 00:09:07.234
As the studio continued to grow, Disney was able to make more ambitious, more expensive, movies,

00:09:07.624 --> 00:09:12.974
the first of which was one I’m sure you will have seen, Snow White and the Seven Dwarves.

00:09:14.174 --> 00:09:18.594
Before Snow White, Disney mainly made short films, and Snow

00:09:18.594 --> 00:09:23.444
White was the first animated feature film, the first long film.

00:09:24.624 --> 00:09:29.124
Now, by modern standards, it’s quite short, it’s only 1 hour and

00:09:29.324 --> 00:09:33.174
28 minutes, but it was really pushing the boundaries for Disney.

00:09:34.284 --> 00:09:39.774
When Walt Disney first suggested it to his animators, they weren’t all sold on

00:09:39.774 --> 00:09:44.794
the idea, they didn’t all think that it was sensible, but Disney was convinced.

00:09:45.834 --> 00:09:51.584
